outputs.output_descr:
The expected outputs include:

1) Country-led poverty-environment mainstreaming programmes;
2) Joint UNDP-UNEP regional support programmes and regional communities of practice on environmental mainstreaming;
3) Global knowledge products and services on environmental mainstreaming.

PEI Kenya: Expected project outputs include:
•	Strengthened Understanding of Poverty and Environmental Linkages Within Government Ministries, Institutions, and other Stakeholders;  
•	Strengthened national Capacity in Economic Valuation of Environment and Natural Resources and integrated (economic, social, and environment) Assessment Methods; 
•	Capacity of Key Stakeholders Strengthened to Integrate Poverty Environment Linkages in Sector and District Development Plans and Budgets and Monitoring Systems;  
•	Strengthened Community Capacity for Sustainable Utilization of Environment and Natural Resources; and 
•	Support Provided for Coordination and Tracking of Environment Components of the District Development Plans and MDGs

The general objective of the project is the relief of poverty through the improvement of the integrated management of solid waste system.  The project will contribute to the alleviation of poverty from the development of knowledge, capacities, strategies, instruments and tools, including social, poverty and gender variables into the planning processes of the integrated management of solid waste at national and local (in Arequipa as pilot) levels.  Synergies between the gradual formalization of recyclers and environmental, social and economic opportunities will be identified and pursued.  

The work in the solid waste sector is an adaptive solution to minimize extreme poverty for vulnerable populations and the project will promote activities that will have a long term impact in the reduction of poverty levels and in the financial sustainability of recycling associations.  With the contribution of United Nations Volunteers, the project will promote an environmental friendly and segregation culture through a local volunteering approach and citizen participation.  

The 5 principal results of the project are:
1.	Institutional and capacity strengthening of the Ministry of the Environment through the integration of social, poverty and gender variables into the solid waste management system in Peru;  
2.	Institutional and capacity strengthening in the Provincial Municipality of Arequipa to improve the integrated management of solid waste through the incorporation of social, poverty and gender variables.  
3.	Strengthened recyclers associations and favorable conditions towards long term financial sustainability;  
4.	The population of Arequipa mobilized and a waste-friendly and recycling culture generated;
5.	The experiences of the project have been systematized and replication opportunities have been promoted.
